<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"By_Native_Americans">By Nat=
ive Americans</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: By Nativ=
e Americans"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<ul><li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuki_language" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Yuki language">Yuki language</a> in <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California" title=3D"California">California</a>=
 has an octal system because the speakers count using the spaces between th=
eir fingers rather than the fingers themselves.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-2">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup></li>
<li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pame_language" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Pame language">Pamean languages</a> in <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mexico" title=3D"Mexico">Mexico</a> also have an o=
ctal system, because some of their speakers "count the knuckles of the clos=
ed fist for each hand (excluding the thumb), so that two hands equals eight=
."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"By_Europeans">By Europeans<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: By Europeans"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ul><li>It has been suggested that the reconstructed <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Proto-Indo-European" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Prot=
o-Indo-European">Proto-Indo-European (PIE)</a> word for "nine" might be rel=
ated to the PIE word for "new".  Based on this, some have speculated that p=
roto-Indo-Europeans used an octal number system, though the evidence suppor=
ting this is slim.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>In 1668, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wilkins" title=
=3D"John Wilkins">John Wilkins</a> in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/An_Essay_towards_a_Real_Character,_and_a_Philosophical_Language" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"An Essay towards a Real Character, and a Philos=
ophical Language">An Essay towards a Real Character, and a Philosophical La=
nguage</a></i> proposed use of base 8 instead of 10 "because the way of Dic=
hotomy or Bipartition being the most natural and easie kind of Division, th=
at Number is capable of this down to an Unite".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-5">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup></li>
<li>In 1716, King <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_XII_of_S=
weden" title=3D"Charles XII of Sweden">Charles XII of Sweden</a> asked <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emanuel_Swedenborg" title=3D"Emanuel S=
wedenborg">Emanuel Swedenborg</a> to elaborate a number system based on 64 =
instead of 10. Swedenborg argued, however, that for people with less intell=
igence than the king such a big base would be too difficult and instead pro=
posed 8 as the base. In 1718 Swedenborg wrote (but did not publish) a manus=
cript: "<i>En ny rekenkonst som om vexlas wid Thalet 8 i stelle then wanlig=
a wid Thalet 10</i>" ("A new arithmetic (or art of counting) which changes =
at the Number 8 instead of the usual at the Number 10"). The numbers 1=E2=
=80=937 are there denoted by the consonants l, s, n, m, t, f, u (v) and zer=
o by the vowel o. Thus 8 =3D "lo", 16 =3D "so", 24 =3D "no", 64 =3D "loo", =
512 =3D "looo" etc. Numbers with consecutive consonants are pronounced with=
 vowel sounds between in accordance with a special rule.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite=
_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Writing under the pseudonym "Hirossa Ap-Iccim" in <i><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Gentleman%27s_Magazine" title=3D"The Gentleman's=
 Magazine">The Gentleman's Magazine</a></i>, (London) July 1745, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Jones_(reverend)" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Hugh Jones (reverend)">Hugh Jones</a> proposed an octal system fo=
r British coins, weights and measures. "Whereas reason and convenience indi=
cate to us an uniform standard for all quantities; which I shall call the <=
i>Georgian standard</i>; and that is only to divide every integer in each <=
i>species</i> into eight equal parts, and every part again into 8 real or i=
maginary particles, as far as is necessary. For tho' all nations count univ=
ersally by <i>tens</i> (originally occasioned by the number of digits on bo=
th hands) yet 8 is a far more complete and commodious number; since it is d=
ivisible into halves, quarters, and half quarters (or units) without a frac=
tion, of which subdivision <i>ten</i> is uncapable...." In a later treatise=
 on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Jones_(reverend)#Publicat=
ions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hugh Jones (reverend)">Octave computat=
ion</a> (1753) Jones concluded: "Arithmetic by <i>Octaves</i> seems most ag=
reeable to the Nature of Things, and therefore may be called Natural Arithm=
etic in Opposition to that now in Use, by Decades; which may be esteemed Ar=
tificial Arithmetic."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>In 1801, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Anderson_of_Her=
miston" title=3D"James Anderson of Hermiston">James Anderson</a> criticized=
 the French for basing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_=
system" title=3D"Metric system">metric system</a> on decimal arithmetic.  H=
e suggested base 8, for which he coined the term <i>octal</i>. His work was=
 intended as recreational mathematics, but he suggested a purely octal syst=
em of weights and measures and observed that the existing system of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_units_of_measurement" title=3D"En=
glish units of measurement">English units</a> was already, to a remarkable =
extent, an octal system.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>In the mid-19th century, Alfred B. Taylor concluded that "Our octonary =
[base 8] <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radix" title=3D"Radix">ra=
dix</a> is, therefore, beyond all comparison the "<i>best possible one</i>"=
 for an arithmetical system." The proposal included a graphical notation fo=
r the digits and new names for the numbers, suggesting that we should count=
 "<i>un</i>, <i>du</i>, <i>the</i>, <i>fo</i>, <i>pa</i>, <i>se</i>, <i>ki<=
/i>, <i>unty</i>, <i>unty-un</i>, <i>unty-du</i>" and so on, with successiv=
e multiples of eight named "<i>unty</i>, <i>duty</i>, <i>thety</i>, <i>foty=
</i>, <i>paty</i>, <i>sety</i>, <i>kity</i> and <i>under</i>." So, for exam=
ple, the number 65 (101 in octal) would be spoken in octonary as <i>under-u=
n</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-10"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> Taylor also republished some of Swedenborg's work on octal as =
an appendix to the above-cited publications.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_computers"><span class=
=3D"anchor" id=3D"\nnn"></span>In computers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: In computers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Octal became widely used in computing when systems such as the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNIVAC_1050" title=3D"UNIVAC 1050">UNIVAC=
 1050</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PDP-8" title=3D"PDP-8">=
PDP-8</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ICT_1900_series" title=
=3D"ICT 1900 series">ICL 1900</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/IBM_mainframe" title=3D"IBM mainframe">IBM mainframes</a> employed <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Six-bit_character_code" title=3D"Six-b=
it character code">6-bit</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/12-b=
it_computing" title=3D"12-bit computing">12-bit</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/24-bit_computing" title=3D"24-bit computing">24-bit</a> =
or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/36-bit_computing" title=3D"36-b=
it computing">36-bit</a> words. Octal was an ideal abbreviation of binary f=
or these machines because their word size is divisible by three (each octal=
 digit represents three binary digits). So two, four, eight or twelve digit=
s could concisely display an entire <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Word_(computer_architecture)" title=3D"Word (computer architecture)">mach=
ine word</a>. It also cut costs by allowing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Nixie_tube" title=3D"Nixie tube">Nixie tubes</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seven-segment_display" title=3D"Seven-segment dis=
play">seven-segment displays</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Calculator" title=3D"Calculator">calculators</a> to be used for the ope=
rator consoles, where binary displays were too complex to use, decimal disp=
lays needed complex hardware to convert radices, and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexadecimal" title=3D"Hexadecimal">hexadecimal</a> displ=
ays needed to display more numerals.
</p><p>All modern computing platforms, however, use 16-, 32-, or 64-bit wor=
ds, further divided into <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octet_(co=
mputing)" title=3D"Octet (computing)">eight-bit bytes</a>. On such systems =
three octal digits per byte would be required, with the most significant oc=
tal digit representing two binary digits (plus one bit of the next signific=
ant byte, if any). Octal representation of a 16-bit word requires 6&nbsp;di=
gits, but the most significant octal digit represents (quite inelegantly) o=
nly one bit (0 or 1). This representation offers no way to easily read the =
most significant byte, because it is smeared over four octal digits. Theref=
ore, hexadecimal is more commonly used in programming languages today, sinc=
e two hexadecimal digits exactly specify one byte.  Some platforms with a p=
ower-of-two word size still have instruction subwords that are more easily =
understood if displayed in octal; this includes the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/PDP-11" title=3D"PDP-11">PDP-11</a> and <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motorola_68000_family" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Motorola 68000 family">Motorola 68000 family</a>.  The modern-day ubiqu=
itous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X86_architecture" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"X86 architecture">x86 architecture</a> belongs to this=
 category as well, but octal is rarely used on this platform, although cert=
ain properties of the binary encoding of opcodes become more readily appare=
nt when displayed in octal, e.g. the ModRM byte, which is divided into fiel=
ds of 2, 3, and 3 bits, so octal can be useful in describing these encoding=
s. Before the availability of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asse=
mbler_(computing)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Assembler (computing)">as=
semblers</a>, some programmers would handcode programs in octal; for instan=
ce, Dick Whipple and John Arnold wrote <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Tiny_BASIC" title=3D"Tiny BASIC">Tiny BASIC Extended</a> directly in m=
achine code, using octal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Octal is sometimes used in computing instead of hexadecimal, perhaps=
 most often in modern times in conjunction with <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/File_permissions" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"File permiss=
ions">file permissions</a> under <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U=
nix" title=3D"Unix">Unix</a> systems (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Chmod" title=3D"Chmod">chmod</a>). It has the advantage of not requ=
iring any extra symbols as digits (the hexadecimal system is base-16 and th=
erefore needs six additional symbols beyond 0=E2=80=939).
</p><p>In programming languages, octal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Literal_(computer_programming)" title=3D"Literal (computer programming=
)">literals</a> are typically identified with a variety of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prefix" title=3D"Prefix">prefixes</a>, including t=
he digit <code>0</code>, the letters <code>o</code> or <code>q</code>, the =
digit=E2=80=93letter combination <code>0o</code>, or the symbol <code>&amp;=
</code><sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <code>$</code>. In <i>M=
otorola convention</i>, octal numbers are prefixed with <code>@</code>, whe=
reas a small (or capital<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DRI_1983_CPM86-PG_13-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-DRI=
_1983_CPM86-PG-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) letter <code>o</code><sup id=3D"cite_ref-DR=
I_1983_CPM86-PG_13-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Octal#cite_note-DRI_1983_CPM86-PG-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <code>q</code>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-DRI_1983_CPM86-PG_13-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-DRI_1983_CPM86-PG-13"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> is added as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suffix" title=
=3D"Suffix">postfix</a> following the <i>Intel convention</i>.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Kueveler-Schwoch_1996_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-Kueveler-Schwoch_1996-14"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kueveler-Schwoch_2007_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-Kueveler-Schwoch_2007-15"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concurrent_DOS" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Concurrent DOS">Concurrent DOS</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiuser_DOS" title=3D"Multiuser DOS">Multi=
user DOS</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/REAL/32" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"REAL/32">REAL/32</a> as well as in <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DOS_Plus" title=3D"DOS Plus">DOS Plus</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DR-DOS" title=3D"DR-DOS">DR-DOS</a> var=
ious <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environment_variable" title=
=3D"Environment variable">environment variables</a> like <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%25$CLS%25" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"%$CLS%">$=
CLS</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%25$ON%25" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"%$ON%">$ON</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%=
25$OFF%25" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"%$OFF%">$OFF</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%25$HEADER%25" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"%$H=
EADER%">$HEADER</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%25$FOOTER%=
25" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"%$FOOTER%">$FOOTER</a> support an <code>=
\nnn</code> octal number notation,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Paul_1997_NWDOSTIP_16=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite=
_note-Paul_1997_NWDOSTIP-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Paul_2002_CLS_1=
7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cit=
e_note-Paul_2002_CLS-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-CCI_1997_HELP_18-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_no=
te-CCI_1997_HELP-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and DR-DOS <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/DEBUG" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"DEBUG">DEBUG</a> utilizes <=
code>\</code> to prefix octal numbers as well.
</p><p>For example, the literal 73 (base 8) might be represented as <code>0=
73</code>, <code>o73</code>, <code>q73</code>, <code>0o73</code>, <code>\73=
</code>, <code>@73</code>, <code>&amp;73</code>, <code>$73</code> or <code>=
73o</code> in various languages.
</p><p>Newer languages have been abandoning the prefix <code>0</code>, as d=
ecimal numbers are often represented with leading zeroes.  The prefix <code=
>q</code> was introduced to avoid the prefix <code>o</code> being mistaken =
for a zero, while the prefix <code>0o</code> was introduced to avoid starti=
ng a numerical literal with an alphabetic character (like <code>o</code> or=
 <code>q</code>), since these might cause the literal to be confused with a=
 variable name.  The prefix <code>0o</code> also follows the model set by t=
he prefix <code>0x</code> used for hexadecimal literals in the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_(programming_language)" title=3D"C (programm=
ing language)">C language</a>; it is supported by <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Haskell_(programming_language)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Haskell (programming language)">Haskell</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-1=
9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OCaml" title=3D"OCa=
ml">OCaml</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title=3D"Python (progr=
amming language)">Python</a> as of version 3.0,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-21=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raku_(programming_la=
nguage)" title=3D"Raku (programming language)">Raku</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cit=
e_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(progr=
amming_language)" title=3D"Ruby (programming language)">Ruby</a>,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Octal#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tc=
l" title=3D"Tcl">Tcl</a> as of version 9,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-24"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PHP" title=3D"PHP">PHP</a>=
 as of version 8.1,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rust_(programming_language)" title=3D"Rust (prog=
ramming language)">Rust</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ECMAScript" title=3D"ECMAScript">ECM=
AScript</a> as of ECMAScript 6<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> (th=
e prefix <code>0</code> originally stood for base 8 in <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript" title=3D"JavaScript">JavaScript</a> but co=
uld cause confusion,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octal#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>28<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> therefore it =
has been discouraged in ECMAScript 3 and dropped in ECMAScript 5<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O=
ctal#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>).
</p><p>Octal numbers that are used in some programming languages (C, <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl" title=3D"Perl">Perl</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PostScript" title=3D"PostScript">PostScri=
pt</a>...) for textual/graphical representations of byte strings when some =
byte values (unrepresented in a code page, non-graphical, having special me=
aning in current context or otherwise undesired) have to be to <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Escape_character" title=3D"Escape character">e=
scaped</a> as <code>\nnn</code>. Octal representation may be particularly h=
andy with non-ASCII bytes of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UTF-8=
" title=3D"UTF-8">UTF-8</a>, which encodes groups of 6 bits, and where any =
start byte has octal value <code>\3nn</code> and any continuation byte has =
octal value <code>\2nn</code>.
</p><p>Octal was also used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flo=
ating-point_arithmetic" title=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">floating point<=
/a> in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferranti_Atlas" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ferranti Atlas">Ferranti Atlas</a> (1962), <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burroughs_B5500" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Burroughs B5500">Burroughs B5500</a> (1964), <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Burroughs_B5700" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Burrough=
s B5700">Burroughs B5700</a> (1971), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Burroughs_B6700" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Burroughs B6700">Burroug=
hs B6700</a> (1971) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burroughs_=
B7700" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Burroughs B7700">Burroughs B7700</a> =
(1972) computers.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_aviation">In aviation</h=
3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: In aviation"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transponder_(aeronautics)" titl=
e=3D"Transponder (aeronautics)">Transponders</a> in aircraft transmit a "sq=
uawk" <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transponder_(aeronautics)#Tr=
ansponder_codes" title=3D"Transponder (aeronautics)">code</a>, expressed as=
 a four-octal-digit number, when interrogated by ground radar. This code is=
 used to distinguish different aircraft on the radar screen.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Conversion_between_bases">C=
onversion between bases</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Conversion between bases"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Decimal_to_octal_conversion=
">Decimal to octal conversion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Decimal to octal conversion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_of_successive_Euclid=
ean_division_by_8">Method of successive Euclidean division by 8</h4><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Method of successive Euclidean div=
ision by 8"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>To convert an integer written in decimal to octal, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division" title=3D"Euclidean division">divide=
</a> the original number by the largest possible power of 8 and divide the =
remainders by successively smaller powers of 8 until the power is 1. The oc=
tal representation is formed by the quotients, written in the order generat=
ed by the algorithm.
For example, to convert 125<sub>10</sub> to octal:
</p>
<dl><dd>125 =3D 8<sup>2</sup> =C3=97 <b>1</b> + 61</dd>
<dd>61 =3D 8<sup>1</sup> =C3=97 <b>7</b> + 5</dd>
<dd>5 =3D 8<sup>0</sup> =C3=97 <b>5</b> + 0</dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 125<sub>10</sub> =3D 175<sub>8</sub>.
</p><p>Another example:
</p>
<dl><dd>900 =3D 8<sup>3</sup> =C3=97 <b>1</b> + 388</dd>
<dd>388 =3D 8<sup>2</sup> =C3=97 <b>6</b> + 4</dd>
<dd>4 =3D 8<sup>1</sup> =C3=97 <b>0</b> + 4</dd>
<dd>4 =3D 8<sup>0</sup> =C3=97 <b>4</b> + 0</dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 900<sub>10</sub> =3D 1604<sub>8</sub>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_of_successive_multip=
lication_by_8">Method of successive multiplication by 8</h4><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sec=
tion=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Method of successive multiplication by 8"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>To convert a decimal fraction to octal, multiply by 8; the integer part =
of the result is the first digit of the octal fraction. Repeat the process =
with the fractional part of the result, until it is null or within acceptab=
le error bounds.
</p><p>Example: Convert 0.1640625 to octal:
</p>
<dl><dd>0.1640625=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=898 =3D 1.3125 =3D <b>1</b> + 0.3125=
</dd>
<dd>0.3125=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=898 =3D 2.5 =3D <b>2</b> + 0.5</dd>
<dd>0.5=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=898 =3D 4.0 =3D <b>4</b> + 0</dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 0.1640625<sub>10</sub> =3D 0.124<sub>8</sub>.
</p><p>These two methods can be combined to handle decimal numbers with bot=
h integer and fractional parts, using the first on the integer part and the=
 second on the fractional part.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_of_successive_duplic=
ation">Method of successive duplication</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=
=3D"Edit section: Method of successive duplication"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To convert an integer written in decimal to octal, prefix the number wit=
h "0.". Perform the following steps for as long as digits remain on the rig=
ht side of the radix:
Double the value to the left side of the radix, using <i>octal</i> rules, m=
ove the radix point one digit rightward, and then place the doubled value u=
nderneath the current value so that the radix points align. If the moved ra=
dix point crosses over a digit that is 8 or 9, convert it to 0 or 1 and add=
 the carry to the next leftward digit of the current value. <i>Add</i> <i>o=
ctally</i> those digits to the left of the radix and simply drop down those=
 digits to the right, without modification.
</p><p>Example:
</p>
<pre> 0.4 9 1 8 decimal value
  +0
 ---------
   4.9 1 8
  +1 0
  --------
   6 1.1 8
  +1 4 2
  --------
   7 5 3.8
  +1 7 2 6
  --------
 1 1 4 6 6. octal value
</pre>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Octal_to_decimal_conversion=
">Octal to decimal conversion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Octal to decimal conversion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To convert a number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">k</span> to decimal, use the formula that defines its base-8 represen=
tation:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e k=3D\sum _{i=3D0}^{n}\left(a_{i}\times 8^{i}\right)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>k</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <munderover>
          <mo>=E2=88=91<!-- =E2=88=91 --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>i</mi>
            <mo>=3D</mo>
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
          </mrow>
        </munderover>
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <msub>
              <mi>a</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>i</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
            <mo>=C3=97<!-- =C3=97 --></mo>
            <msup>
              <mn>8</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>i</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle k=3D\sum _{i=
=3D0}^{n}\left(a_{i}\times 8^{i}\right)}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/31d9ec7cb0c2ca3fbe4fb30be97b473232a04136" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -3.005ex; width:17.014ex; height:6.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle k=
=3D\sum _{i=3D0}^{n}\left(a_{i}\times 8^{i}\right)}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>In this formula, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sub><i>i</i></sub></sp=
an> is an individual octal digit being converted, where <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">i</span> is the position of the digi=
t (counting from 0 for the right-most digit).
</p><p>Example: Convert 764<sub>8</sub> to decimal:
</p>
<dl><dd>764<sub>8</sub> =3D 7=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=898<sup>2</sup> + 6=E2=
=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=898<sup>1</sup> + 4=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=898<sup>0</sup>=
  =3D 448 + 48 + 4 =3D 500<sub>10</sub></dd></dl>
<p>For double-digit octal numbers this method amounts to multiplying the le=
ad digit by 8 and adding the second digit to get the total.
</p><p>Example: 65<sub>8</sub> =3D 6=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=898 + 5 =3D 53<su=
b>10</sub>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_of_successive_duplic=
ation_2">Method of successive duplication</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Method of successive duplication"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To convert octals to decimals, prefix the number with "0.". Perform the =
following steps for as long as digits remain on the right side of the radix=
: Double the value to the left side of the radix, using <i>decimal</i> rule=
s, move the radix point one digit rightward, and then place the doubled val=
ue underneath the current value so that the radix points align. <i>Subtract=
</i> <i>decimally</i> those digits to the left of the radix and simply drop=
 down those digits to the right, without modification.
</p><p>Example:
</p>
<pre> 0.1 1 4 6 6  octal value
  -0
 -----------
   1.1 4 6 6
  -  2
  ----------
     9.4 6 6
  -  1 8
  ----------
     7 6.6 6
  -  1 5 2
  ----------
     6 1 4.6
  -  1 2 2 8
  ----------
     4 9 1 8. decimal value
</pre>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Octal_to_binary_conversion"=
>Octal to binary conversion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Octal to binary conversion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>To convert octal to binary, replace each octal digit by its binary repre=
sentation.
</p><p>Example: Convert 51<sub>8</sub> to binary:
</p>
<dl><dd>5<sub>8</sub> =3D 101<sub>2</sub></dd>
<dd>1<sub>8</sub> =3D 001<sub>2</sub></dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 51<sub>8</sub> =3D 101 001<sub>2</sub>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Binary_to_octal_conversion"=
>Binary to octal conversion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Binary to octal conversion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The process is the reverse of the previous algorithm. The binary digits =
are grouped by threes, starting from the least significant bit and proceedi=
ng to the left and to the right.  Add leading zeroes (or trailing zeroes to=
 the right of decimal point) to fill out the last group of three if necessa=
ry.  Then replace each trio with the equivalent octal digit.
</p><p>For instance, convert binary 1010111100 to octal:
</p>
<dl><dd><table class=3D"wikitable" cellpadding=3D"4">

<tbody><tr align=3D"center">
<td>001</td>
<td>010</td>
<td>111</td>
<td>100
</td></tr>
<tr align=3D"center">
<td>1</td>
<td>2</td>
<td>7</td>
<td>4
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 1010111100<sub>2</sub> =3D 1274<sub>8</sub>.
</p><p>Convert binary 11100.01001 to octal:
</p>
<dl><dd><table class=3D"wikitable" cellpadding=3D"4">

<tbody><tr align=3D"center">
<td>011</td>
<td>100</td>
<td>&nbsp;.&nbsp;</td>
<td>010</td>
<td>010
</td></tr>
<tr align=3D"center">
<td>3</td>
<td>4</td>
<td>&nbsp;.&nbsp;</td>
<td>2</td>
<td>2
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 11100.01001<sub>2</sub> =3D 34.22<sub>8</sub>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Octal_to_hexadecimal_conver=
sion">Octal to hexadecimal conversion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=
=3D"Edit section: Octal to hexadecimal conversion"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The conversion is made in two steps using binary as an intermediate base=
. Octal is converted to binary and then binary to hexadecimal, grouping dig=
its by fours, which correspond each to a hexadecimal digit.
</p><p>For instance, convert octal 1057 to hexadecimal:
</p>
<dl><dd>To binary:</dd></dl>
<dl><dd><table class=3D"wikitable" cellpadding=3D"4">

<tbody><tr align=3D"center">
<td>1</td>
<td>0</td>
<td>5</td>
<td>7
</td></tr>
<tr align=3D"center">
<td>001</td>
<td>000</td>
<td>101</td>
<td>111
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<dl><dd>then to hexadecimal:</dd></dl>
<dl><dd><table class=3D"wikitable" cellpadding=3D"4">

<tbody><tr align=3D"center">
<td>0010</td>
<td>0010</td>
<td>1111
</td></tr>
<tr align=3D"center">
<td>2</td>
<td>2</td>
<td>F
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 1057<sub>8</sub> =3D 22F<sub>16</sub>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hexadecimal_to_octal_conver=
sion">Hexadecimal to octal conversion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=
=3D"Edit section: Hexadecimal to octal conversion"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Hexadecimal to octal conversion proceeds by first converting the hexadec=
imal digits to 4-bit binary values, then regrouping the binary bits into 3-=
bit octal digits.
</p><p>For example, to convert 3FA5<sub>16</sub>:
</p>
<dl><dd>To binary:</dd></dl>
<dl><dd><table class=3D"wikitable" cellpadding=3D"4">

<tbody><tr align=3D"center">
<td>3</td>
<td>F</td>
<td>A</td>
<td>5
</td></tr>
<tr align=3D"center">
<td>0011</td>
<td>1111</td>
<td>1010</td>
<td>0101
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<dl><dd>then to octal:</dd></dl>
<dl><dd><table class=3D"wikitable" cellpadding=3D"4">

<tbody><tr align=3D"center">
<td>0</td>
<td>011</td>
<td>111</td>
<td>110</td>
<td>100</td>
<td>101
</td></tr>
<tr align=3D"center">
<td>0</td>
<td>3</td>
<td>7</td>
<td>6</td>
<td>4</td>
<td>5
</td></tr></tbody></table></dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, 3FA5<sub>16</sub> =3D 37645<sub>8</sub>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Real_numbers">Real numbers<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DOctal&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Real numbers"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fractions">Fractions</h3><s=
